TypeScript does not yell at you for a good reason.

Would it have made a difference if you were to add a parameter that would have been unused?

    doSomething&lt;Person&gt;((personThatWouldNotBeUsed) =&gt; {
        console.log(&#39;Hello world 2&#39;);
        return {
            firstName: &#39;john&#39;,
            age: 10
        }
    })

You saying &quot;I expect a function that takes a `Person` as a parameter, and returns a `Person` as a result&quot; merely means that you will *call* whatever function with a `Person` object, and that you will treat the returned result as a `Person` object. Whether the function actually uses the supplied parameter is completely up to it.

---

TL;DR - You can&#39;t force the callback your consumer passes to use all of the parameters, nor should you be able to. It is up to the consumer to decide whether it wants to use the supplied parameter or not.

