For a given `VipCustomer`s, you can query with:

&lt;pre&gt;&lt;code&gt;my_vip_customer.&lt;b&gt;vip_consommations&lt;/b&gt;.aggregate(
    &lt;b&gt;total=Sum(&#39;food__price&#39;)&lt;/b&gt;
)[&#39;total&#39;]&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/pre&gt;

We thus aggregate over the set of *related* `Consommation`s, and we then aggregate over all the related `Food`s of these `Consommation`s, and their corresponding `price`.

If there are no related `Consommation`s, or no related `Food`s of these `Consommation`s, then the sum will return `None`, instead of `0`. We can add `or 0` to convert a `None` to an `0` here:

&lt;pre&gt;&lt;code&gt;my_vip_customer.vip_consommations.aggregate(
    total=Sum(&#39;food__price&#39;)
)[&#39;total&#39;] &lt;b&gt;or 0&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/pre&gt;

or for all `Customer`s, we can annotate this with:

&lt;pre&gt;&lt;code&gt;VipCustomer.objects.annotate(
    &lt;b&gt;total=Sum(&#39;vip_consommations__food__price&#39;)&lt;/b&gt;
)&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/pre&gt;

Here the `VipCustomer`s that arise from this, will have an extra attribute `.total` that contains the sum of the `price`s of the related `Food`s of the related `Consommation`s.

